      },
      "date": "2017-11-30 11:55:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(1 comment)\n\nI checked history of changes and it seems that this is not such regression as I thought. Meanwhile I found one case that looks not safe. Waiting for is_bl_done() is polling that bl_done flag, which is set in ldlm_cancel_callback() only if !ldlm_is_cancel(). At the same time in ldlm_handle_bl_callback() we have:\n\nif (ldlm_is_cancel_on_block(lock))\n\tldlm_set_cancel(lock)\n\nTherefore later ldlm_cancel_callback() will not set ldlm_bl_done because ldlm_is_cancel() is set and will wait for is_bl_done until timeout.\nIsn't it? Or that case with cancel_on_block is handled somehow?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "c9da90c2a355b318b64ec1d017234fa7f8d25aff",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 135,
        "name": "Vitaly Fertman",
        "email": "vitaly.fertman@hpe.com",
        "username": "vitaly_fertman"
      },
      "date": "2017-11-30 13:10:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n\nJinshan, is is_bl_done is moved upper, do we still need it in ldlm_cancel_callback() ? iirc, it was introduced to protect cleanup_resource vs bl thread race, because the clearup_resource does not pass the async flag down; it is covered by the upper check now.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "1cbba19259a26d198a2b4dcac18cd13a84f19fb2",
      "author": {
